description:
WHY (process gap, NOT an implementation claim): the shorthand "durable sync/async shipped" is narrower than reality. Verified on main: tf-lfxs/#567 = GREEN spike + SDD only (tiny-firegrid validation, NOT production rollout); tf-lf9p/#573 = production dependent-session BARRIER ONLY (session.prompt(), session.start(), firegrid.sessions.prompt() now wait for reflected context internally via awaitSessionDependentContext(...); test: createOrLoad->prompt waits without explicit whenReady). tf-lf9p NON-GOALS explicitly: do NOT generalize to every callable binding; do NOT delete whenReady; record candidate follow-ups. The broad placeholder tf-82a3 ("Production sync-handshake semantics on createOrLoad/call channels") was CLOSED AS SUPERSEDED by the narrow tf-lf9p — so the broad scope was dropped, not delivered. This bead re-captures that residual.

SCOPE: enumerate EVERY callable / request-row-then-reflect operation across the public surface + bindings, and classify each into exactly one of:
  (a) ALREADY blocking/reflection-owned (e.g. session-dependent writes via tf-lf9p);
  (b) SHOULD remain async / request-ack (no sync handshake wanted);
  (c) NEEDS the sync handshake moved into the binding / dependent-op (work to do);
  (d) redundant explicit barrier API to DELETE/DEPRECATE LATER (e.g. whenReady only where truly redundant).
Produce a rollout PLAN (ordered slices) from the classification.

ACCEPTANCE (so "SDD/spike green" is never again read as "production shipped globally"): per-operation SOURCE EVIDENCE (file:line of the binding behavior) + a TEST proving the classification, for every enumerated op. No global "shipped" claim without per-op proof. Deliverable = an audit doc (classification table + rollout plan) + the per-op evidence/tests; docs-first, no broad impl in this bead (the rollout plan spawns the impl slices).

LINKS: tf-lfxs (#567 spike+SDD), tf-lf9p (#573 session-dependent-write slice), tf-82a3 (broad placeholder, prematurely closed-as-superseded), docs SDD_FIREGRID_DURABLE_CHANNELS_SYNC_ASYNC.md, + current experiment-doc pressure.

DOC GUIDANCE (immediate, correct as of now): omitting explicit whenReady before session.prompt/session.start IS correct (that production path shipped via tf-lf9p). It is NOT correct to imply the whole sync/async channel model is globally implemented — only the session-dependent-write slice is.

Known issue from Phase-1 Lane 2 Option A bridge.

When agent-tool wait_for is implemented as race-inside-Activity, the match path remains durable because Stream.runHead reads durable stream rows, but the timeout side uses in-memory Effect.sleep inside the Activity. If the host/engine scope recycles while the wait is in flight, the Activity retries and the timeout restarts from timeoutMs instead of preserving an absolute DurableClock deadline.

Exposure: bounded liveness/SLA degradation, not correctness corruption. A wait_for timeout can take longer than requested across one or more host bounces; with repeated bounces before the timer completes, timeout can be extended until one generation stays alive long enough. It should not corrupt replay, lose durable rows, or return incorrect matches.

Fix direction: migrate WaitForWorkflow from Activity-internal race to engine-native streamWaitAny / streamWait with persisted absolute deadline once the primitive exists.

Acceptance for closure:
- wait_for uses engine-native wait with persisted absolute deadline across recycle;
- restart/bounce sim proves timeout deadline is not re-armed from scratch;
- same-generation match and timeout behavior remains green;
- PR/finding references the Phase-1 Lane 2 bridge caveat and closes this known issue.
